Extended Biography
Sco B. Weingart is a leader, federal policy maker,
and award-winning solar building a thoughtful
future through human-centered tenology. Before
direing initiatives across academic, cultural, and
public seors, he spent time as a hiorian, a librarian, a
data scienti, and (really) a professional circus
performer.
Weingart serves as the Chief Data Ocer and Founding
Direor of the Oce of Data and Evaluation (ODE) at
the National Endowment for the Humanities (NEH).
In his capacity as Chief Data Ocer and as a member of
NEHs senior leadership team, Weingart oversees data
operations, compliance, analysis, and rategy at the
federal agency. Under Weingarts direion, the ODE
supports NEH data-informed decision making and
keeps the public informed on the ate of the
humanities in the United States. It does so through
assessments of grant programs for equitability and
impa; through humanities aivities reports to the
White House, Congress, and the public; and through
ongoing partnerships with non-prot, governmental,
resear, and educational organizations.
In addition to his NEH service, Weingart is a Resear
Aliate with the University of Edinburghs Centre
for Data, Culture & Society; an Advisory Commiee
Member of the Library of Congress Copyright Public
Modernization Commiee; and an Advisory Board
Member of the Posen Digital Library of Jewish Culture
and Civilization. He formerly direed the University of
Notre Dames Navari Family Center for Digital
Solarship and Carnegie Mellon Universitys Digital
Humanities program. In both roles, Weingart led large
teams pursuing and supporting the critical use of
emerging tenologies by solars, librarians, and
udents across disciplines. He served in these roles
while maintaining an aive resear and teaing
portfolio. Weingart previously served as a treasurer for
the Alliance of Digital Humanities Organizations and
an executive council member of the Association for
Computers and the Humanities.
Weingart is a prize-
winning author of dozens
of books and articles. e
Network Turnpublished
by Cambridge University
Press in 2020 and co-authored with Ruth Ahnert,
Sebaian Ahnert, and Nicole Colemanis a manifeo
for adoption of network approaes and metaphors in

eory is dedicated to the books central claim. e

popular introduory textbook for digital hiory. e

work has been translated into and published in
Chinese, Dut, Italian, Portuguese, Russian,
Spanish, & Ukrainian.
e Alliance of Digital Humanities Organizations
awarded the preigious Paul Fortier Prize in Digital
Humanities to Weingart and his colleague Jeana
Jorgensen in 2011. Weingarts resear has been funded
by the National Initutes of Health, the National
Science Foundation, the National Endowment for the
